13 “O dear little piece of mine that so you have inscribed, 14 that, as the earthly minds see, 15 not to grasp in a triangle two obtuse,
16 thus you see the contingent things 17 rather than they are in themselves, gazing at the point 18 to which all the times are present;
19 while I was joined to Virgil 20 up the mountain that the souls care 21 and descending into the dead world,
22 said to me were of my future life 23 grave words, perhaps that I may feel 24 well tetragon to the blows of fortune;
25 for which my desire would be content 26 to understand what fortune approaches me: 27 because a foreseen arrow comes slower.”

